{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":36282,"duration_api_ms":36249,"num_turns":5,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"73c9bc50-a45f-4f71-99f4-34677c986431","total_cost_usd":0.222774,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":20162,"cache_read_input_tokens":133113,"output_tokens":1207,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":20162,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":6,"outputTokens":1207,"cacheReadInputTokens":133113,"cacheCreationInputTokens":20162,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.222774,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Amendment fr-2-e4469e42 identifies a real, well-understood concurrency bug in the trace-capture test. The test uses `#[tokio::test(flavor = \"multi_thread\")]` with `tracing::subscriber::set_default(...)`, which only installs the subscriber on the current thread. After await points in `service.invoke(request).await`, the future can resume on a different Tokio worker thread where the test subscriber is not installed, causing trace events to be lost and assertions to fail intermittently. The fix (switching to `current_thread` flavor or using a cross-thread capture mechanism) is straightforward and correct.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-2-e4469e42","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified at lines 572-637: the test uses `#[tokio::test(flavor = \"multi_thread\")]` combined with `tracing::subscriber::set_default(subscriber)` (line 595). `set_default` is thread-local — it only installs the subscriber on the calling thread. With `multi_thread` flavor, the `service.invoke(request).await` at line 596 has await points that allow the future to be scheduled onto a different Tokio worker thread. Any `tracing` events emitted after such a migration (e.g., the \"invocation completed\" span event) would not be captured by the test's subscriber, causing the assertions at lines 603-637 to fail intermittently. This is not a theoretical concern — it is a well-documented interaction between tokio's multi-thread runtime and tracing's thread-local default subscriber. Switching to `flavor = \"current_thread\"` is the simplest correct fix since this test has no need for multi-thread semantics; alternatively, using a globally-scoped capture layer would also work."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"7793e882-46ae-4388-9d76-1ed926ce4363"}
